		<article id="comment-1412" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/89e73bc0be13bb5a395a4140290ee177?s=44&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite><b class="fn"><a href='http://elidourado.com/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Eli</a></b> <span>Post author</span></cite><a href="http://elidourado.com/blog/political-assassination/#comment-1412"><time datetime="2011-04-25T22:30:59+00:00">April 25, 2011 at 10:30 pm</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>My immediate reaction is that having a bounty system in place would select for relatively unobjectionable successors. If a dictator is belligerent and killed via bounty, belligerent types will be less likely to try to succeed him, although I suppose you could tell an alternative story in which only super-bloodthirsty types are willing to take the risk. It probably depends on the comparative statics and the reasonableness of the powers using the bounty system.</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

			<div class="reply">
							</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
